liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A brilliant innings comes to an end. Out of nothing really, a pull shot to a nothing short ball and Crawley finally plays on - after a couple of earlier near misses. He goes for a magnificent 189 off 182 balls. "What an incredible innings and a standing applause from everyone in the ground," former Australian paceman Glenn McGrath says on TMS. "A 200 would have been really fitting. "Crawley has really set his team up really well here."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: CRAWLEY PLAYED ON! HE'S FINALLY OUT!

children.content: A brilliant innings comes to an end.
Out of nothing really, a pull shot to a nothing short ball and Crawley finally plays on - after a couple of earlier near misses.
He goes for a magnificent 189 off 182 balls.
"What an incredible innings and a standing applause from everyone in the ground," former Australian paceman Glenn McGrath says on TMS.
"Crawley has really set his team up really well here."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Here are some numbers for that session. Australia bowled 25 overs. They took one wicket. England, meanwhile, clattered 178 runs off those 150 balls. That's 7.12 runs per over. England now only trails by 78 runs. Good grief, what a game-changing session.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: TEA: England 2-239 (Crawley 132, Root 44)

children.content: Here are some numbers for that session.
Australia bowled 25 overs. They took one wicket.
England, meanwhile, clattered 178 runs off those 150 balls.
England now only trails by 78 runs.
Good grief, what a game-changing session.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Slashed away in fittingly aggressive fashion into the off side and Crawley reaches three figures off just 93 balls. This has been pure domination. He's threatened to do this all series and finally broken through.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Zak Crawley has his first Ashes century!!
